By Muluneh¶

Introduction¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

The dataset contains 84,853 loans with 15 features ('Term', 'LoanStatus', 'BorrowerAPR', 'LenderYield', 'EstimatedEffectiveYield', 'ProsperRating (numeric)', 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', 'ListingCategory (numeric)', 'Occupation', 'EmploymentStatus', 'DebtToIncomeRatio', 'IncomeRange', 'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'MonthlyLoanPayment')

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

What i'm intersted in this dataset is what factors affect the lone outcome status and the borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) rate beside to this are the difference between loan depending on how large the origional loan amount was?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I have seen that the total loan amount will have a great effect on the borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) of the loan which the most larger the total loan amount, the most the lower the borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR). I also clearly seen that the borrowers stated monthly income, loan term, Prosper rating, employment status will also have effects on the APR.

LoanStatus Distribution¶

In [385]:
def loneStatus_bar_graph():
    base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    type_order = df_lone['LoanStatus'].value_counts().index

    sns.countplot(data=df_lone,x='LoanStatus',color = base_color,order= type_order);
    type_count = df_lone['LoanStatus'].value_counts()
    n_count = df_lone['LoanStatus'].value_counts().sum()
    locs, labels = plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
        count = type_count[label.get_text()]
        pct_string ='{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_count)
        plt.text(loc,count+1,pct_string,ha='center',color ='black',fontsize=12);
    from matplotlib import rcParams
    rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 14,5
    plt.xlabel("Loan Status")
    plt.ylabel("Frequency")
    plt.title("Graph Represents The Loan Status");
loneStatus_bar_graph()

As we can see from the categorical lone status graph the current lone satus is 66.7% which is the hightst distrubtion the completed and the chargedoff is the second and the thired heigest distribution respectively.

def BorrowerAPR_graph():
    plt.figure(figsize=[20, 5])
    # histogram on left, example of too-large bin size
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    bins = np.arange(0,df_lone['BorrowerAPR'].max()+0.1,0.1)
    plt.hist(data = df_lone, x = 'BorrowerAPR', bins = bins);
    plt.xlabel('Borrower APR')
    plt.ylabel("Frequency")
    plt.title("Graph represent The distribution of Borrower APR");
    # histogram on left, example of too-small bin size
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    bins = np.arange(0,df_lone['BorrowerAPR'].max()+0.01,0.01)
    plt.hist(data = df_lone, x = 'BorrowerAPR', bins = bins);
    plt.xlabel('Borrower APR')
    plt.ylabel("Frequency")

    plt.title("Graph represent The distribution of Borrower APR")

def debetToIncomeRation_hist_graph():
    plt.figure(figsize = [8,5])
    bin_edges = np.arange(0, df_lone['DebtToIncomeRatio'].max()+1, 0.1)
    sns.distplot(df_lone['DebtToIncomeRatio'], bins = bin_edges, kde = False,hist_kws = {'alpha' : 1})

    plt.title("Graph represent The distribution of DebtToIncomeRatio");

  • The plot the DebtToIncomeRation is unimodal with the highest peack point between 0.2-0.3 the distribtution is righ skewed

  • The lone origional amout is a mutlimodel distribution with a multiple peack and values xk multiple.

    Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

    The distributions of stated monthly income is highly right screwed. Most stated monthly incomes are less than 30k, but some of them are incredibly high, like greater than 100k. Surprisingly, most of borrowers with greater than 100k monthly income only loan less than 5k dollars. So, the very large stated monthly income may be made up. Overall, Less than 0.3 percent borrowers have stated monthly income greater than 30k, these can be seemed as outlier for the following analysis, so it is better to remove borrower records with income greater than 30k. There is no need to perform any transformations.

    I can make the following poits after the plot

    1. The loan amount increases with better rating.
    2. The borrower APR decreases with better rating.
    3. Interestingly, the relationship between borrower APR and loan amount turns from negative to slightly positive when the Prosper ratings are increased from HR to A or better.
    4. This may because people with A or AA ratings tend to borrow more money, increasting APR could prevent them borrow even more and maximize the profit.
    5. On the oter side people with lower ratings tend to borrow less money, decreasing APR could encourage them to borrow more.
